Ask HN: What to do with a fairly hefty work learning stipend?
text:
My work recently instated a learning stipend. I'd rather not say the exact amount, but it's in the low thousands per year.

I'm a backend engineer at a growing company that also does ad hoc devops work when needed. I love software engineering books, so that's something I'd definitely spend this on, but there's no way I'll be able to read thousands of dollars of books a year.

What are some other good resources I can take advantage of here? It's a really generous stipend and I'd like to make the most of it. It's restricted to things that related to my current work.

Show HN: Rundmz – library for runnable Markdown for tutorials and demos
text: I put together a library in Golang which lets you use Markdown in a literate programming style. Blockquotes and comments can specify associated actions, calling back into your Go code. This lets you create tutorials and scripts which can be viewed in a browser or run on the command line. We use this in the OpenZiti project (https://github.com/openziti/ziti) for our tutorials and demos. I thought others might be interested in using the code or even just the concept.

title: Engineering Excellence Drives Everything We Do
Show HN: We just enabled Vercel's preview comments on our docs page
text:
We've been having a hard time getting feedback on our docs. Some people post GitHub issues or send us pull requests, but we've heard that the friction is too great for little things like typos, etc.

We thought Vercel's preview might be a decent solution to lower the friction for people with Vercel accounts.

Vercel injects a code bundle into the site, similar to a browser extension, automatically setting up a commenting system and UI for us.

If you want to see how it looks, check it out here: https://docs.plasmo.com/
